    "visualization_explanation": "The dataset contains 4-dimensional geospatial data: x/y coordinates (quantitative interval scales), state abbreviations (nominal categorical), regions (ordinal categorical), and capital names (nominal categorical). Synthetic positioning follows real geographic relationships with x-axis representing longitude clusters and y-axis latitude bands, maintaining relative positions while optimizing chart space. Regional color coding uses categorical hues from Material Design guidelines. The bubble chart maximizes data-ink ratio by removing axis lines while preserving geographic relationships through positional encoding. Cairo's principles of salience are applied through hexagon markers and direct labeling, creating immediate state recognition. Color saturation (80% opacity) maintains figure-ground contrast while allowing marker overlap visualization. Regional clustering emerges naturally with west (blue) leftmost, south (yellow) dominant in lower half, and northeast (pink) upper-right, matching real US geography patterns."
